problem:
The values of a function $f(x)$ are given below:

\begin{tabular}{|c||c|c|c|c|c|} \hline $x$ & 3 & 4 & 5 & 6 & 7 \\ \hline $f(x)$ & 10 & 17 & 26 & 37 & 50 \\ \hline \end{tabular}Evaluate $f^{-1}\left(f^{-1}(50)\times f^{-1}(10)+f^{-1}(26)\right)$.
model_solution:
## Step 1:  Evaluate the innermost inverse functions.
\[
\begin{aligned}
f^{-1}(50) &= 7 \\
f^{-1}(10) &= 3 \\
f^{-1}(26) &= 5
\end{aligned}
\]

## Step  2:  Multiply the results of the three inverse functions.
\[
\begin{aligned}
7 \times 3 + 5 &= 21 + 5 \\
&= 26
\end{aligned}
\]

## Step 3: Evaluate the outermost inverse function.
\[
\begin{aligned}
f^{-1}(26) &= 5
\end{aligned}
\]
